Implemented BtMenuView, which is somewhat like an item view, but is actually a
subclass of QMenu. It can be used as a submenu to view data in some model. It
only uses the first columns of data from the model. In case the model is a tree
model, all model items with children are displayed as submenus. Items without
children are displayed like QActions. If any of the the latter are triggered, a
triggered(QModelIndex) signal is emitted with the model index of that item. The
menu itself is reconstructed every time its shown.

Given the bookshelf model and the bookshelf model filters, BtMenuView can easily
be used to display works in the menus of the buttons of the new display window
headers which were recently implemented.

Usage example:

  void MyWidget::initMenus() {
    // ...
    m_myMenu = new QMenu(this);
    // ...
    m_modelMenu = new BtMenuView(m_myMenu);
    m_modelMenu->setIcon(QIcon(":/myIcon.png"));
    m_modelMenu->setModel(m_model);
    m_myMenu->addMenu(m_modelMenu);
    connect(m_modelMenu, SIGNAL(triggered(QModelIndex)),
            this,        SLOT(slotItemClicked(QModelIndex));
  }

  void MyWidget::slotItemClicked(QModelIndex itemIndex) {
    if (!itemIndex.isValid()) return;

    QString text(m_model->data(itemIndex, Qt::DisplayRole)).toString();
    if (text.isEmpty()) return;

    qDebug() << "Item " << text << " selected";
    // ...
  }


